\begin_layout Section
Measurements - Aperture Photometry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Calculating Photomatry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a fits file and the sky coordinates of a celestial object (star, galaxy
 or anything that emits enough light) that is seen in the fits file image,
 calculating this object's photomatry is rather simple.
 The fits file gives the information of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

light count
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in each pixel of the image, so to calculate the object's photometry one
 needs to choose an aperture radius (preferably as close to the object as
 possible) and sum the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

light count
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the pixels that are within the aperture.
 In reality we had to deal with some complexity that will be decribed in
 the next few sections, as well as our solutions to these problems.
 The measured flux of an object will be denoted as DN.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Aperture Photometry package for python
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most of the calculating work is done by Photutils packages
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Flex URL
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

https://photutils.readthedocs.io/en/stable/aperture.html
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 that are designed to calculate photometry, when given a fits file, sky
 coordinates and an aperture radius.
 These packages calculate the each object's DN in the catalog's data units
 and give a more accurate result than just summing the pixels, since the
 summing should be in the shape a circle within the aperture radius, but
 when summing in pixels we get a shape that is not congruent with the circle,
 so a more complcated calculation is requierd here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Units
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The value, or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

light count
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, of each pixel varies between catalogs.
 We intended to find the photometry values in magnitudes, so for each catalog
 there is a different convertion and a different gain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
SDSS - an SDSS fits file counts light using nanomaggy (nMgy) units.
 A "maggy" is the flux f of the source relative to the standard source 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}$
\end_inset

 (which defines the zeropoint of the magnitude scale).
 The convertion from nMgy to magnitudes is the following
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Flex URL
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

http://www.sdss3.org/dr8/algorithms/magnitudes.php#nmgy
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
m=-2.5log_{10}(DN\times10^{-9})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
PS1 - for the convertion from PS1 data units to magnitudes we use the zero
 point, which is the magnitude of an object with an electron count of 1.
 PS1's zero point is normalized and equals 25 for all the fits files, so
 the convertion from data units to magnitudes is the following
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Flex URL
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

https://outerspace.stsci.edu/display/PANSTARRS/PS1+Stack+images
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
m=-2.5log_{10}DN+25+2.5log_{10}(EXPTIME)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Where EXPTIME is the exposure time for a stack, and it ig given in the fits
 file header under 'EXPTIME'.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Sky-units to Pixels
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a fits file and an object's sky coordinates, we want to be able to
 convert distances from sky units (arc seconds) to pixels in the fits image,
 so if we choose an aperture radius in arc seconds, we can find the aperture
 radius in pixels.
 The convertion varies between the catalogs:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
PS1 - the convertion is the following:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
arcsec=\frac{1}{3600\cdot CDELT1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Where CDELT1 is the ratio of degrees to pixel in each fits file, and it
 can be found in the header under 'CDELT1'.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
SDSS - the convertion is the following: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
arcsec=\frac{1}{\sqrt{(CD1\_2\cdot3600)^{2}+(CD2\_2\cdot3600)^{2}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Where CD1_2 and CD2_2 are RA and DEC degrees per row pixel, and they can
 be found in the header under 'CD1_2' and 'CD2_2'.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Later we can use this covertion to convert the aperture radius to calculate
 the background, as described in the next segment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An important part of calculating photometry, is subtructing the image's
 background from the DN, since there might be a different light emitter
 close to the object (or in front of it) that can add light to the DN.
 To calculate the background we set 3 radii: small, medium and large, such
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $radii=[radius,2\cdot radius,3\cdot radius]$
\end_inset

, where radius is the aperture radius used for the DN measurment.
 The background is calculated in the ring between medium and large radii
 (the big ring), since between the small and the medium radii some light
 from the object might be present.
 Here we denote DN as the matrix of the values that are within the big ring.
 The background is calculated using:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
bg=median(DN)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

And the background error is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
bg\_error=\frac{SDT(DN)}{\sqrt{n}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the calculation of the error I neglect the poisson distribution error,
 since the statistical error (as we saw in our measurments) is the dominent
 one.
 Equations 5 and 6 give as the median and the error of the background in
 one pixel, so to calculate the DN without the background:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
corrected\_DN=DN-bg\cdot\pi r^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Where r is the aperture radius (the small radius).
 To find the total error we do the same:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
bg\_error\_tot=bg\_error\cdot\pi r^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Errors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An important factor we need to address here is the gain: in CCD imaging,
 gain refers to the magnitude of amplification a given system will produce
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Flex URL
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

https://www.photometrics.com/learn/imaging-topics/gain
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The DN if calculated using:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
DN=\frac{electrons}{gain}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Where electrons is the number of electrons that encountered the measuring
 instrument.
 We can find each catalog's gain in the fits file header: in PS1 it's under
 'HIERARCH CELL.GAIN' and in SDSS it's under 'NMGY' (NMGY is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{gain}$
\end_inset

 so for SDSS 
\begin_inset Formula $DN=NMGY\cdot electrons$
\end_inset

).
 The gain is important when calculating the errors, since we know that the
 electron counts is a poisson distribution, but we need to find the error
 for DN.
 DN's error consists of 2 errors: the poisson distribution error of the
 electron count and the background error.
 The first error we calculate with:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
pois\_error=\frac{1}{gain}\sqrt{DN\cdot gain}=\sqrt{\frac{DN}{gain}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the second error is calculated in equation 8.
 we find the total error:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
DN\_error=\sqrt{pois\_error^{2}+bg\_error\_tot^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The final step in calculating the errors is converting then to magnitudes.
 To do so we convert the following to magnitudes: corrected_DN, corrected_DN
 + error, corrected_DN - error.
 We don't have symetric errors here so we get 2 different errors when converting
 to magnitude: up and down.
 We calculate them:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
down\_error=|(corrected\_DN+error)-corrected\_DN|
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
up\_error=|(corrected\_DN-error)-corrected\_DN|
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In equtions 12 and 13 are the final errors in magnitudes, and the error
 range is 
\begin_inset Formula $[corrected\_DN-down\_error,corrected\_DN+up\_error]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Aperture Radius
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For SDSS images the Aperture radius is 1.5 arcsec.
 For PS1 images the aperure radius is calculated using PS1 catalog information,
 and this is covered in section 3.2 - 
\series bold
Testing and Statistics - PS1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Testing and Statistics - PS1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
During the writing of the program, I did all the calculations on some carefully
 picked stars (instead of galaxies).
 This is because stars are, roughfly, a point source of light, whereas the
 light from galaxies tends to be spread.
 I used the sdss image tool
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Flex URL
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

http://skyserver.sdss.org/dr15/en/tools/chart/navi.aspx
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 to pick about 48 bright stars that have fits files and are visible in all
 5 bands.
 After choosing the stars I uploaded their coordinates to the Pan-STARRS
 (will be reffered as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

PS1
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 from here) Catalog Search
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Flex URL
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

https://catalogs.mast.stsci.edu/panstarrs/
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This search can give us information on weather a star is seen in PS1 (as
 described above) and it can give us the stars' photometry accordind to
 PS1 and how to calculate it.
 This is a very important tool that can be used to check the correctness
 of the code, since we can compare the program's results to PS1's results.
 We noticed the PS1 search output provides information on two options to
 calculate the photometry:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For each object and in each band, psf minor FWHM and psf major FWHM are
 given.
 We can use the average of the two as the aperture radius for the measurment
 and divide the result by 0.9375, since the psf captures only 93.75% of the
 object's light
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
reference is needed here
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For each object and in each band, aperture radius and aperture filling factor
 are given.
 We can use the apreture radius as radius for the measerment and divide
 thr result by the aperture filling factor (from similar reasons to the
 previuos option, only now the percentage of light captured within the aperture
 radius varies).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I've tried both calculations in the program to see which one gets me a result
 similar to the ps1 calculated photometry, and found that the best option
 is the second one - using the filling factor.
 This desicion was made after comparing the differences between ps1 calculated
 photometry and my calculated photomotry (hereinafter will be refferd as
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the difference
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

), in both options.
 For the first option, the median of the differences per band is at most
 
\begin_inset Formula $\backsim0.48$
\end_inset

 Mag (see Table 1a), whereas for the second option it's at most 
\begin_inset Formula $\backsim0.082$
\end_inset

 Mag (see table 1b).
 It is importand the mention here that for option 1 the differnce is calculated
 be subtracting my measure from ps1's measure (meaning - I measure less
 light), and for option 2 it's the opposite (meaning, I measure more light).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float table
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The medians and and standart deviations of the differences in each band
 for the 48 selected stars using the two options for aperture radii (option
 1- psf radius, option 2 - aperture radion with filling factor)
