\begin_layout Standard
After analyzing all the data shwon in table 1 and figures 2-3, we have decided
 to use option 2 to measure the photometry in the ps1 catalog, so from now
 on I will reffer only to option 2 in the data and plots.
 The meaning of a 0.08 Mag difference between the calculation is an approximately
 8% difference, so we can conclude that for the measurment of objects with
 less than 20.5 Mag, my calculations are reliable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next step was to make sure that the calculated errors match ps1's calculated
 errors (in ps1's data the errors that match option 2 are under 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ApMagErr
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

), so I created a plot of ps1's calculated errors vs.
 my calculated errors for each band after the clipping (Figure 3).
 In each plot there's a black line, representing 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x$
\end_inset

, to have a better view on the differences between the errors.
 We can see that most of the points in the plots are either on or very close
 to the black line, showing us that not only the errors are from the same
 order of magnitude, but are also very close to each other, conforming our
 errors calculation for objects with measurmet of up to 20.5 Mag.
\end_layout

